english:
  title: Preface to the Hongwu Correct Rhymes
  author: Shin Suk-ju
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The study of phonology is known to be the most difficult to master. This is because the customs and geography of the four regions differ, and so too does the vital breath that moves through them. Since sound is born from this vital breath, the so-called four tones and seven rhymes naturally vary according to locality. Ever since Shen Yue compiled his rhyme table, southern phonetic elements became mixed in, and learned men recognized this as a flaw. Yet through all the dynasties, none had undertaken to correct and regulate it.

    When the Hongwu Emperor of the Ming, observing how these discrepancies had led to confusion and disorder, commanded his scholars to establish a unified standard based on the pure Central Plain pronunciation, thereby creating the Hongwu Correct Rhymes. This became the standard honored by all nations under heaven.

    Our King Sejong the Wise turned his attention to the study of phonology, investigating it to its depths. He created the Hunmin Jeongeum—the Correct Sounds for the Instruction of the People—comprising several tens of characters, through which all the sounds of the ten thousand things across the four directions can be transmitted. Our Eastern scholars thereby first came to understand that the four tones and seven sounds are inherently complete in our own language—not merely as matters of characters and rhymes, but in their very essence.

    Since our Eastern kingdom has long served the Middle Kingdom yet our language remains unintelligible, we must rely upon interpretation. The King therefore commanded that the Hongwu Correct Rhymes be translated. He appointed the current Minister of Rites Seong Sam-mun, the Vice Director of Agriculture Cao Bian-an, the County Magistrate of Geumsan Kim Jeung, the former Ritual Master Sun Su-san, and myself Suk-ju to investigate the ancients and verify the texts. The Prince of Suyang and the Prince of Gyeyang oversaw its compilation. All participated directly in reviewing and perfecting the work, aligning it with the seven sounds and the four tones, harmonizing it through distinctions of clarity and murmur, establishing the vertical and horizontal principles, and thereby achieving perfect correctness without defect.

    Yet since pronunciation varies by region, errors in transmission are manifold. We were therefore commanded to seek correction from Chinese scholars and learned men. Through journeys back and forth, numbering seven or eight times, we consulted with numerous individuals. Beijing, being the gathering place of all nations, afforded us many opportunities during our long travels to converse and clarify matters—not only with great scholars but with emissaries from distant lands, monks, and common soldiers alike. We exhausted all possible variations between standard and colloquial usage. When the Emperor's envoys came to our land, if they were learned men, we would seek their correction as well. We transcribed more than ten drafts, laboring through countless revisions over eight long years, until what had been established as correct became increasingly beyond doubt.

    When King Munjong, while still Crown Prince, served the sage with sagely support and participated in determining the sounds and rhymes, and upon ascending the throne appointed myself and others—the former Judge No Sam, the current Censor Kwon In, and the Vice Director Lim Won-joon—to undertake further review and correction. In the Hongwu Correct Rhymes, all rhyming characters that were either combined or separated have been properly regulated. However, the ordering of the seven sounds does not follow their natural sequence. We dared not arbitrarily alter this, so we retained the original arrangement while distributing the initial consonants to their places at the beginning of each character within the various rhyme categories. We employed the Hunmin Jeongeum in place of the traditional reverse-cutting method, yet since one cannot ignore colloquial pronunciations and alternative usages, we added annotations below each character. For instances still difficult to convey, we added brief explanatory notes to illustrate the principle. We also separately attached the Four Tones Examination as established by King Sejong, and compiled explanatory guidelines to serve as a standard.

    When His Majesty ascended to the throne, he promptly commanded that this work be printed and distributed widely. As I had earlier received the command from my late sovereigns to compose this preface and record these events, I now do so.

    Reflecting upon this matter: phonology extends horizontally across the seven rhymes and vertically across the four tones. The four tones originated in the regions south of the Yangtze, and the seven sounds arose in the Western regions. It was not until the Song scholars created their rhyme tables that the warp and weft were finally unified into one system. The seven sounds became thirty-six initial consonants; the four retroflex consonants and the one labial light aspirate have long fallen into disuse, and predecessors have already modified them—these should not be rigidly preserved out of attachment to antiquity.

    The four tones are: level, rising, departing, and entering. For fully voiced characters, the level tone approaches the light aspirate, while rising, departing, and entering tones approach the fully clear. This is how the world pronounces them, yet people do not understand why. Moreover, every syllable has both an initial and a final sound, which is the natural principle of forming a character. Yet for the entering tone alone, the world carelessly omits the final sound—a practice without justification. Even in Mongol rhyme tables and Huang Gongshao's Rhyme Compendium, the entering tone likewise omits the final sound. How can this be? Such anomalies are not singular, and they remain matters of doubt.

    Though we made many corrections through repeated consultation, we never encountered a master of phonology who could fully explain the subtleties of articulation and rhyming categories. We could only pursue the matter through careful listening and repeated study, seeking to understand the principles of voicing, aspiration, and the openness and closedness of articulation—attempting thereby to clarify what is most difficult. This is why our long and painstaking labor has yielded but modest results.

    We scholars are shallow in learning and narrow in understanding, unable to plumb the deepest mysteries or illuminate the sage's wisdom. Yet our great King Sejong, endowed with innate sagacity, possessed such brilliance and comprehensive understanding that nothing lay beyond his reach. He thoroughly investigated the origins and development of phonology, carefully weighed and determined all principles, unified the seven sounds and four tones into a single warp and weft, and brought them to perfect correctness. What our Eastern land had not understood in a thousand years can now be learned in less than ten days. If one truly reflects deeply and repeatedly studies these principles, how could the study of phonology remain difficult to master?

    The ancients said: "Though Sanskrit is transmitted to the Middle Kingdom, the classics of Confucius could not reach India—not because of sound, but because of writing." Yet surely wherever there is sound, there is written form. How could writing exist without sound? Now, through translation with the Hunmin Jeongeum, sound and rhyme are brought into perfect harmony. We need no longer resort to the laborious and complicated methods of tonal harmony, phonetic distance, forward cutting, or reverse cutting. Simply by opening one's mouth, one attains the correct sound with absolute precision. Why then should we worry about the variations in wind and soil across different lands?

    The marvelous creations of all our sage kings are perfection itself, surpassing both ancient and modern times. And the virtue of His Majesty in continuing their great work shines forth ever more brilliantly upon the achievements of his predecessors.
  footnotes:
    - The Hunmin Jeongeum (訓民正音, Correct Sounds for the Instruction of the People) was King Sejong's revolutionary phonetic system created in 1443, designed to represent Korean and Chinese sounds accurately and make literacy accessible to commoners.
    - Shen Yue (441-513) was a Chinese poet and scholar whose work on rhyme classification became foundational but was criticized for incorporating Southern Chinese phonetic elements.
    - 'The ''four tones'' refer to the tonal distinctions in Middle Chinese: level (平), rising (上), departing (去), and entering (入) tones.'
    - The reference to Sanskrit (梵音) and Confucian classics unable to reach India reflects the concern that linguistic barriers prevented the full transmission of Chinese culture and learning.
    - The 'warp and weft' (經緯) metaphor represents the systematic coordination of rhyming categories and tonal patterns into a unified whole.
